{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6fce4a83-02a7-4e10-bd82-add2d9bcf887","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer workload manifests needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you still hit issues after updating, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` workload is installed, and check that your project's `TargetFramework` aligns with the SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6ef572d1-ebd4-42d3-849a-76660db944a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase for this.","outputTokens":255,"requestId":"9433:1EB0D5:1490A27:16F51FF:6A066FFF"},"id":"6f31de54-cbaa-441c-a150-c8719aa43a92","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:59:50.793Z","parentId":"1473cc3c-8d67-4e9e-bdb3-5691e294de6c"}
